05512nam a22007695i 9780674037427DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222000mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740374277 a10.4159/97806740374272doi  a(DE-B1597)574372  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aLB2806.36 ǂb I57 2000eb 7aEDU0340002bisacsh04a371.0100aInside Charter Schools :bThe Paradox of Radical Decentralization /ced. by Bruce Fuller. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (301 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Growing Charter Schools, Decentering the State -- t1 The Public Square, Big or Small? Charter Schools in Political Context -- t2 We Hold on to Our Kids,We Hold on Tight: Tandem Charters in Michigan -- t3 An Empowering Spirit Is Not Enough: A Latino Charter School Struggles over Leadership -- t4 Selling Air: New England Parents Spark a New Revolution -- t5 Diversity and Inequality: Montera Charter High School -- t6 Losing Public Accountability: A Home Schooling Charter -- t7 Teachers as Communitarians: A Charter School Cooperative in Minnesota -- t8 Breaking Away or Pulling Together? Making Decentralization Work -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDeepening disaffection with conventional public schools has inspired flight to private schools, home schooling, and new alternatives, such as charter schools. Barely a decade old, the charter school movement has attracted a colorful band of supporters, from presidential candidates, to ethnic activists, to the religious Right. At present there are about 1,700 charter schools, with total enrollment estimated to reach one million early in the century. Yet, until now, little has been known about the inner workings of these small, inventive schools that rely on public money but are largely independent of local school boards. Inside Charter Schools takes readers into six strikingly different schools, from an evangelical home-schooling charter in California to a back-to-basics charter in a black neighborhood in Lansing, Michigan. With a keen eye for human aspirations and dilemmas, the authors provide incisive analysis of the challenges and problems facing this young movement. Do charter schools really spur innovation, or do they simply exacerbate tribal forms of American pluralism? Inside Charter Schools provides shrewd and illuminating studies of the struggles and achievements of these new schools, and offers practical lessons for educators, scholars, policymakers, and parents.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aEDUCATION / Educational Policy & Reform / General.2bisacsh1 aFuller, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFuller, Bruce, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHuerta, Luis A, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuerta, Luis A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJellison Holme, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRofes, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStuart Wells, Amy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVasudeva, Ash, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWexler, Edward, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYancey, Patty, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZernike, Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Ba